# Havas.2 Neuro-Metric Analysis Report (Comprehensive)

## Overview
This report details the full battery of tests applied to the `Havas.2` dataset to replicate the Tunad/Gaia analysis methodologies.
It separates the analysis into **Images** (static neuro-metrics) and **Videos** (time-series derived metrics).

## 1. Methodology & Hypothesis Testing

| Hypothesis / Test | Description | Applied to | Status |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Central Hypothesis** | Do neural indices explain sales/conversion (CTR)? | Image & Video | **Done** |
| **"5 Seconds" Rule** | Do the first 5 seconds explain performance better than the whole? | Video | **Done** |
| **Peak Score** | Do high-intensity moments (Peak Engagement) drive performance? | Video | **Done** |
| **Fluency Index** | Does ease of processing (Engagement / Focus) drive performance? | Image & Video | **Done** |
| **Quartile Analysis** | Do top-performing creatives (Top 25% CTR) have different neuro profiles than bottom ones? | Image & Video | **Done** |

---

## 2. Video Analysis Results
*Sample: 2076 creatives*

### A. Central Hypothesis (Correlation)
*Goal: measure linear relationship between neuro-metrics and CTR.*
- **Fluency Index**: `r = 0.08` (**Positive & Significant**, p<0.001).
- **Neural Engagement (Mean)**: `r = 0.05` (**Positive & Significant**, p=0.03).
- **Focus (Mean)**: `r = -0.07` (**Negative & Significant**, p=0.002).
- *Observation*: Higher engagement and "fluency" (ease of processing) correlate with better performance. High sustained focus correlates with worse performance (perhaps indicating confusion or cognitive load).

### B. Advanced Methodologies
#### "5 Seconds" Hypothesis
*Goal: Test if the start of the video is more predictive.*
- **Neural Engagement (5s)**: `r = -0.03` (Not significant, p=0.11).
- **Conclusion**: For this dataset, variables from the first 5 seconds were **less predictive** than the full video average. The "5 Second Rule" was **refuted** in this specific context.

#### Peak Score
*Goal: Test if peak emotional moments matter more than averages.*
- **Peak Engagement**: `r = -0.05` (**Negative & Significant**, p=0.01).
- **Conclusion**: Surprisingly, higher *peak* engagement was associated with slightly *lower* CTR, whereas higher *average* engagement was positive. This might suggest consistency is more important than spikes.

#### Quartile Analysis (Top 25% vs Bottom 25%)
*Goal: Compare neuro profiles of the best vs worst performers.*

| Metric | Top 25% CTR (Mean) | Bottom 25% CTR (Mean) | Difference |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Fluency Index** | **3.26** | 2.69 | **+21.2%** |
| **Neural Engagement** | **69.23** | 65.76 | **+5.3%** |
| **Focus** | 28.08 | 31.53 | -11.0% |

- **Insight**: The most successful videos are processed significantly more "fluently" (+21%) and have higher overall engagement (+5%), but require less sustained focus (-11%).

![Video Quartile Analysis](/Users/tomasdefreitascarvalho/.gemini/antigravity/brain/40f72a65-5efc-416f-89ef-18ca4422368b/quartile_Video.png)

### C. Machine Learning & Regression
#### Linear Regression (OLS)
- **R-squared**: `0.03` (Model explains 3% of variance).
- **Significant Predictors**:
    - **Fluency Index**: Positive coefficient (p=0.045).
    - **Engagement (Mean)**: Positive coefficient (p<0.001).
    - **Peak Engagement**: Negative coefficient (p<0.001).

#### Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)
- **R-squared**: `-0.23` (Model performs worse than a simple mean baseline).
- **Interpretation**: The lack of improvement with a non-linear model suggests the relationship is either very weak linear or dominated by noise/other factors not captured in the neuro-metrics.
- **Top Features**: Despite poor performance, the model prioritized **engajamentoneural** and **focus**.

![XGBoost Importance Video](/Users/tomasdefreitascarvalho/.gemini/antigravity/brain/40f72a65-5efc-416f-89ef-18ca4422368b/xgboost_importance_Video.png)

